summary.seg: Cambridge University Library MS Ff.1.27 (Part I) is a miscellany of the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, containing, amongst other texts, Gildas’ De excidio Britanniae (1-14), the Historia Brittonum attributed to Nennius (14-40), an anonymous life of St. Cuthbert (195-202), and the collected works of Gille of Limerick (237-242), a twelfth-century Irish bishop. Probably conceived as a compendium of historical material, the manuscript shows a considerable interest in Irish and Northumbrian history, as suggested by its inclusion of Symeon of Durham’s Historia Dunelmensis Ecclesiae (122-194), Aethelwulf’s De abbatibus (203-215), and the Old English poem known as ‘Durham’ (202).

The complex provenance of the manuscript, which was once bound with Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 66, has been much disputed by scholars. Once thought to have originated at the scriptorium of the Cistercian Abbey at Sawley (Lancs.), the most recent analysis has suggested an origin at Durham Cathedral Priory, thus placing Durham as an important twelfth-century centre for the copying and transmission of historical material (Dumville, 1998). At some point in its history, probably under its ownership by Matthew Parker Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 in the sixteenth-century, the original manuscript was broken up: Ff.1.27 Part I bound with the latter half of a thirteenth-century manuscript from Bury St. Edmunds, and CCCC 66 with the first half of the Bury manuscript (now separated into CCCC 66a).

Despite the composite nature of the manuscript, many of its constituent texts are highly significant within their respective traditions of transmission and textual history. The copy of the Historia Brittonum is a rare recension of the text that explicitly ascribes the work to Nennius Nennius, born 769 A.D. , and is thought to have been copied from the first witness of the Nennian Historia in Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 139. The manuscript’s copy of Symeon of Durham’s Historia is likewise one of the first to name
Symeon of Durham Symeon of Durham, 1060-1130 as author - a feature that does not even appear in the two earliest manuscript witnesses of the text (Durham University Library, MS Cosin V.II.6 and London, British Library, Cotton Faustina A.v). The manuscript’s copy of the Historia de Sancto Cuthberto has been identified as the second oldest copy in existence (Johnson South, 2002), and, uniquely, is followed in the same hand by the latest extant poem in regular Old English metre known to exist, the vernacular poem “Durham”, which describes the fame of the city and its most famous inhabitants, from the “famous writer Bede” to the “gracious, blessed [saint] Cuthbert”.

Though written by several hands, the appearance of the manuscript’s various texts are pleasingly coordinated, each written in two columns, structured by red rubrics and decorated with alternating red and green initials. Some initials, such as those to the opening of Gildas’ De excidio on page 2 and Symeon of Durham’s Historia Dunelmensis on page 123, are finely executed, characterised respectively by intricate foliage and arabesque motifs. A particular highlight of the manuscript’s illumination occurs on page 238, which contains a fully coloured Imago ecclesiae illustrating Gille of Limerick’s De statu ecclesie. Based on a Gothic architectural frame, with arching and arcading reminiscent of stained glass window designs, the image illustrates episcopal and secular church hierarchy, together with the orders of society descending from the emperor and kings.

Perhaps the most codicologically complex manuscript in the University’s collection, the codex is a highly significant witness to the evolution of several textual traditions, and for the dissemination of historical material about the British, Irish and Hiberno-Saxon past. Compiled at the very transition between the late Anglo-Saxon and Anglo-Norman periods, the manuscript shows contemporaries coming to grips with the rich literary legacy of some eight hundred years of historical writing in the British Isles, marshalled here into a diverse compendium that attests to the wealth of historical scholarship in twelfth-century Durham.

Cambridge University Library MS Ff.1.27 (Part II) is a miscellany of the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, containing a selection of historical texts including Gerald of Wales’s Topography of Ireland (pages 253-355), an anonymous life of St. Patrick (pages 453-471), and Rhygyfarch ap Sulien’s Life of St. David (pages 618-636). Probably conceived as a compendium of historical material, the manuscript shows a particular interest in Irish history, saints’ lives and mythology, and also includes a copy of Geoffrey of Monmouth’s Life of Merlin (pages 610-618).

Originating at the Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds, the manuscript is one half of a larger volume, split into two parts by Matthew Parker Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 in the sixteenth century. Now bound with a twelfth-century miscellany of historical texts from Durham (Ff.1.27 Part I), the other half of the Bury manuscript is now Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 66A, which contains material by the French chronicler Jacques de Vitry de Vitry, Jacques, 1170-1240 and diverse cosmological and poetic texts. Probably rearranged by its early modern owner to form a more pleasing collection of texts relating to British and Irish history, Ff.1.27 Part II also contains a sixteenth-century copy of Gerald of Wales’s Itinerary, evidently added at the same time as Parker’s restructuring of the codex.

Written, in its medieval portions, in a fine example of the Gothic hand, the manuscript bears some striking, and finely executed illumination. Historiated initials, such as that of Henry II enthroned (page 262); St Patrick preaching (page 453) and Merlin making a prophecy (page 610), make lavish use of gold leaf, and may be compared, in the design and the quality of the figural depictions, to contemporary illuminated Psalters, such as the thirteenth-century Carrow Psalter (Baltimore, Walters Art Museum, MS W.34). Numerous border decorations, principally occurring in Gerald of Wales’s Topographia (esp. pages 277-344), show thematically diverse scenes, including religious images (for instance the Crucifixion on page 318), aspects of the natural world (e.g. a whale on page 299), and some delightfully vernacular imagery, as in the depiction of a woman embracing a goat and a lion on page 308.

Containing some fine illumination and several important texts pertaining to the history of the British Isles, the manuscript attests to the copying and transmission of historical material at Bury St. Edmunds in the high medieval period. Providing important evidence about the range of historical scholarship at the Abbey, the codex is also notable for its post-medieval history, offering an insight into Matthew Parker’s management of his collection, and how sixteenth-century scholars viewed the relative importance of medieval texts.

supportDesc.condition: The condition of the manuscript is generally good, with fresh, clean-coloured parchment that is not generally darkened or worn. There are, however, some small holes on certain leaves, and evidence of stitching to repair more serious tears, as on page 116. The script, which is largely clear and legible, has occasionally deteriorated in the rubrics, which, as in the bottom right corner of page 120 are now barely legible. Particular damage has occurred at the bottom of page 236, which was previously covered by a strip of parchment added a later date (now removed and inserted at the beginning of the volume).

layoutDesc.layout: Thirty six lines in two columns.

handDesc.handNote: Volume I, containing Gildas and Nennius, from pages 1-40 has been written in one hand, of probable twelfth-century date. A different hand of the twelfth century has written Part III, containing Bede's De Temporum ratione, on pages 73-120. Part IV (122-194) containing Symeon of Durham, appears to have been written in the same twelfth-century hand as Part III. However, pages 191-194 contain matter written in several hands. The Life of Cuthbert from pages 195-202, together with the Old English Durham poem on page 202, have been written in the same hand. Miscellaneous different hands are responsible for the Visiones (217-220); Gilbertus Episcopus Lumicensis (237-242) and the miscellany of regnal lists (243-252).

decoNote.p: Part I (pages 1-40): B initials (15 lines) with foliage infill in similar palette (light blue, green and orange), but by different artists, one initial on burnished gold ground on page 3, the other of powdered gold on page 21.

Part II (pages 41-71): Initial A (16 lines) filled with serpentine dragon on burnished gold ground, with an eagle perching on the top finial on page 41. There is also a 5-line burnished gold B initial on a blue and rose ground on page 41.
Part III (pages 73-120): Red, green and light blue 11-line arabesque initials, as on page 73 and on page 76.
Part IV (pages 122-194): Arabesque initials (8-21 lines) in green, red, light blue and tan, as on page 123; page 131 and page 132. There is also a green and red 6-line foliage initial on page 187.
Part V (pages 195-202): Light blue I initial with red and green arabesque endings, occupying most of page 195.
Parts VI (pages 203-265) and VII (pages 217-220): Green, red and light blue 7-line arabesque initials, as on page 203 and page 221.
A map in green, blue and red, showing the division of the earth by three sons of Noah appears on page 25.
A fully coloured Imago ecclesiae, illustrating Gilbert of Limerick's De statu ecclesiae (pages 237-242) appears on page 238.
The manuscript contains several decorated signes de renvoi and paragraph marks. Grotesques, some emerging from letters, appear on page 3, page 19 and page .

physDesc.additions: The Table of Contents on page i is a Parkerian addition of the sixteenth century. Parker is also responsible for the pagination in red crayon at the top right of each leaf. In the top left-hand corner of each page, a later hand has added a description of that page's contents. Further post-medieval additions to the manuscript page are rare, but there is evidence of a post-medieval pastedown on page 236, since removed and inserted as an addendum strip to the inside of the volume. A note indicating Archbishop Matthew Parker as a previous owner of the manuscript, 'Matthaus Cantuar. 1574' occurs on page 1r.

history.provenance: Probably produced at Durham Cathedral Priory (Meehan, 1994; Norton, 1998); at an early point bound with Cambridge, Corpus Christi College MS 66 (Imago mundi; History of England etc.) which has colophon of 1188 and ex libris of c. 1200 from Cistercian Abbey of Sawley, Yorks. This part of Ff.1.27 is therefore also likely to have been at Sawley. However, Dumville, 1974, argues for later dating (s. xiii) and Sawley origin. For the original order of the Sawley manuscript, see Dumville, 1980. The part of the manuscript previously bound with the Bury portion of Corpus MS 66 (now MS 66a) is likely to be of the same provenance, although written in a different hand.

supportDesc.condition: The condition of the manuscript is broadly good. Compared to Ff.1.27 (Part I) in the same volume, the vellum is relatively intact, bearing few of the holes that are so pervasive in the earlier part of the codex. Where damage has occurred, as on page 527, this has evidently taken place prior to the manuscript's inscription, as text has been written around the holes. On the whole, however, the script is regular and clear, and the manuscript's illuminations, including those containing gold leaf, have not become worn or tarnished. On some pages heavy ruling marks can be seen, as on page 611. The manuscript has also been cut down, as shown by the way in which some of the decoration has missing edges, as on page 610.

physDesc.additions: A sixteenth-century Parkerian Table of Contents has been added to the beginning of the manuscript on the first flyleaf. The top of the first page bears the owner's inscription of Matthew Parker, 'Matthaus Cantuar, 1574'. A sixteenth-century copy of Gerald of Wales's Descriptio Cambriae has been added on pages 473-494 and an index to the manuscript has been added at the end of the codex on the end flyleaves from i-ix by Abraham Whelock, Librarian of the University Library from 1629-53.

history.provenance: Produced at Bury St. Edmunds Abbey. Split into two parts in the sixteenth century, of which Ff.1.27 (Part II) is the second half of the original manuscript, the first half preserved in Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 66A. Owned by Matthew Parker in the sixteenth century, as suggested by an addition to the top of page 1, reading 'Matthaus Cantuar, 1574'.
